<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-710-535  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 710 535.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CommunicationsWeek  Dec 17 1990 n331 p14(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>United broadband of America. (Perspective) (part 2; upgrade plansfor phone system) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Newman, George M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A nationwide fiber optic broadband network policy needscongressional and presidential support in order to spurcompetition and technology development.andP;  Cost estimates forproviding broadband service to every home range from $171 billionto $450 billion.andP;  These costs would be covered by government andprivate contributions.andP;  The Congress should rewrite antitrustlegislation, thus allowing companies to form consortiums andenable cable and telephone companies to cross-own fiber opticnetworks.andP;  A cabinet post should be formed to represent thetelecommunication and high technology industries.andP;  Otherlegislative efforts would include an amendment of theCommunications Act of 1934 to factor in contemporary technologyand a provision to allow the Bell operating companies to enter theinformation service market.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Telecommunications ServicesReorganizationGovernment RegulationDeregulationBroadbandFiber OpticsNetwork ManagementAntitrust LawsLegislationBell Regional Holding Companies.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>